<h3><b>Short Description</b></h3><p class="MsoNormal"><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class="MsoNormal">OPC_LE_MAX_LINES_READ specifies the number of lines to be
read from log file by the opcle at every interval.<o:p></o:p></p>

<h3><b>Long Description</b></h3><p class="MsoNormal"><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class="MsoNormal">Subagent opcle is responsible for monitoring the log files
specified in the policy. Opcle can read a log file in 3 read modes:<o:p></o:p></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><b>Read from the last position:&nbsp;</b><span style="font-size: inherit; letter-spacing: 0.2px; background-color: transparent;">The policy reads only newly added entries written in the log
file while the policy is enabled on the managed node. If the inode of log file
being monitored is changed or file is truncated/rolled over then the entire log
file is read.</span></p><p class="MsoNormal"><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><b>Read from beginning (first time):&nbsp;</b><span style="font-size: inherit; letter-spacing: 0.2px; background-color: transparent;">The policy reads the complete log file each time the policy
is enabled or the agent restarts on the managed node. This ensures that all
entries in the log file are compared with the rules in the policy. Each
successive time that the policy reads the log file, only new (appended) entries
in the log file are processed.</span></p><p class="MsoNormal"><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><b>Read from beginning (always):&nbsp;</b><span style="font-size: inherit; letter-spacing: 0.2px; background-color: transparent;">The policy reads the complete log file every time it detects
that the log file has changed. The policy scans the log file at the specified
polling interval. If no change is detected, the log file is not processed.</span></p><p class="MsoNormal"><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class="MsoNormal">The read mode of a log file policy indicates whether the
policy should process the entire log file or should only process new log file
entries.<o:p></o:p></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"></p><ul><li>OPC_LE_MAX_LINES_READ variable supports for Read from the
last position and Read from beginning (first time) but it not supports Read
from beginning (always).</li><li>OPC_LE_MAX_LINES_READ variable supports only logfile policy
only and not supports windows event log policy.</li></ul><o:p></o:p><p></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><b>Possible Scenarios where&nbsp;
OPC_LE_MAX_LINES_READ variable could be used :</b><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"></p><ul><li>Delayed arrival of opcle alerts while monitoring multiple logfiles
by single logfile policy:<br>Consider a scenario where user wants to monitor dynamic log
files a,b,c,d. Log file a is getting appended very fast than the other 3 files.
In that case if<span style="font-size: inherit; letter-spacing: 0.2px; background-color: transparent;">&nbsp; </span><span style="font-size: inherit; letter-spacing: 0.2px; background-color: transparent;">OPC_LE_MAX_LINES_READ is
0 then opcle will keep monitoring log file “a” until all lines in this file are
processed by opcle. Thus alerts from other 3 files may get delayed.<br></span>We can tackle this situation by setting
OPC_LE_MAX_LINES_READ to value “X”. So, that every log file will be read at max
till “X” lines at each interval. Remaining lines from files will be processed
in next interval.</li><li>Opcle consuming high CPU:<br>Suppose logfile policy have multiple log files to process
and some logfiles are huge or appended very fast. Ocple will process each line
in such file till whole file is read. Such situation may cause opcle to consume
high cpu till files are read/processed. Setting variable OPC_LE_MAX_LINES_READ
we can reduce the number of lines to be read at each interval. It will reduce
the CPU utilization for opcle process.</li></ul><p></p><h2>OPC_COND_EVT_LOG_SRC_PAT </h2><p class="MsoNormal"><o:p></o:p></p><div>

