 <tr>
  <td width="178" valign="top" style="width: 133.5pt; border-right-width: 1pt; border-bottom-width: 1pt; border-left: 1pt solid black; border-right-color: black; border-bottom-color: black; border-image: initial; border-top: none; padding: 0in 5.4pt;">
  <p class="MsoNormal"><span style="line-height: 107%;"><b>Related variables</b><o:p></o:p></span></p>
  </td>
  <td width="504" valign="top" style="width: 5.25in; border-top: none; border-left: none; border-bottom-width: 1pt; border-bottom-color: black; border-right-width: 1pt; border-right-color: black; padding: 0in 5.4pt;">
  <p class="Label"><span lang="EN-US" style="">NA<font face="Calibri, sans-serif"><span style="font-size: 12pt;"><o:p></o:p></span></font></span></p>
  </td>
 </tr>
</tbody></table><h3><b>Short Description</b></h3><p class="MsoNormal"><o:p></o:p></p><p class="MsoNormal">When OPC_LE_CMD_RETRY_ENABLED is TRUE, if the script/command
given in the LOG file path of the LE policy fails, opcle will retry the
script/command 2 more times before sending the failure message<o:p></o:p></p><h3><b>Long Description</b></h3><p class="MsoNormal"><o:p></o:p></p><p class="MsoNormal">The Logfile Encapsulator monitors the log files based on the
conditions specified in the LE policy and sends the appropriate message to the
OM browser.<o:p></o:p></p><p class="MsoNormal">In the LE policy, there i.e. a field "Log file
Source" where the user should specify the log file that the policy should
monitor.<o:p></o:p></p><p class="MsoNormal">This can be done in following ways:<o:p></o:p></p><p class="MsoNormal"><ul><li>Type the drive letter and the full path for the location of
this log file on the appropriate managed node or the absolute path to the file.</li><li>This can be Windows environmental variables (for example
winnt or clusterlog) to make the policies more flexible. The proper syntax for
these variables is &lt;$variablename&gt;.</li><li>It can also be a script or command that returns the path and
name of a log file or any number of logfiles to be monitored. For example, type
&lt;`command`&gt; where command is the name of a script that returns the path
and name of the log file/files you want to monitor.</li></ul><o:p></o:p></p><p class="MsoNormal"><o:p></o:p></p><p class="MsoNormal"><o:p></o:p></p><p class="MsoNormal">During each polling interval, the command specified in the
policy will be executed to dynamically determine the list of log files that are
to be monitored and there are possibilities that the files are overwritten,
added or deleted.<o:p></o:p></p><p class="MsoNormal">Hence, during every polling interval, the internal data
structures of ‘opcle’ are updated:<o:p></o:p></p><p class="MsoNormal"><ul><li>To add/delete the log file from the list of the files to be
monitored based on the latest command output</li><li>Determine if the files are updated or overwritten and set
the read offsets accordingly</li></ul><o:p></o:p></p><p class="MsoNormal"><o:p></o:p></p><p class="MsoNormal">Now, if OPC_LE_CMD_RETRY_ENABLED is TRUE and this script or
command in the LOG file path of the LE policy fails, OPCLE will try to run it 2
more times. If these attempts also result in failure then, the failure message
is sent.<o:p></o:p></p><p class="MsoNormal">For example, In the log file policy, the Log file Source
path can have a command like “ &lt;`dir /b /s C:\temp\*.log`&gt; “ instead of
providing a list of actual files. The files names will be determined
dynamically during every polling interval<o:p></o:p></p><p class="MsoNormal">When there are no files that match the pattern, this command
will fail. But there may be a possibility that some utility deletes and then
recreates the files immediately. So if the same command is executed again,
these files will get listed and the command will be successful instead waiting
till the next polling interval.<o:p></o:p></p><p class="MsoNormal">In such case, if this variable is set to TRUE the command
will be retried up to 2 more times and the listed files can be read by Opcle.
If these attempts also fail, a failure message is sent.<o:p></o:p></p><p class="MsoNormal">Given below is the sample trace when this variable is
enabled and the command execution fails in all the attempts:<o:p></o:p></p><p class="MsoNormal"><b>First retry: </b><o:p></o:p></p><p class="MsoNormal">01/11 14:21:08.442 opcle(2408:1492)[debug]: Previous
execution of cmd : dir /b /s C:\temp\*.log exited with non-zero value. Retrying
1 time <o:p></o:p></p><p class="MsoNormal"><b>Second retry:</b><o:p></o:p></p><p class="MsoNormal">01/11 14:21:08.442 opcle(2408:1492)[debug]: Previous
execution of cmd : dir /b /s C:\temp\*.log exited with non-zero value. Retrying
2 time<o:p></o:p></p><p class="MsoNormal"><b>The second retry also fails and the command is not attempted
again:</b><o:p></o:p></p><p class="MsoNormal">

















































</p><p class="MsoNormal">01/11 14:32:21.895 opcle(2408:1492)[debug]: ERRLIST:
[genproc.c:480]: The process 'dir /b /s C:\temp\*.log' terminated with a
